<br>
<font color=yellow>The words "Corresponding to that" is actually the Greek word antitupon. The NIV translates antitupon as "symbolizes". Baptism is a representation, a copy, a type of something else, according to Peter. A type of what? A symbol of what? Exactly the same analogy he presented with the story of Noah. </font color><br>
<br>
Actually when I looked it up the greek word is translated "figure", as does the KJV, but I don't like the KJV so that isn't really important.  NASB says "corresponding."  I don't encourage people to skip between versions to find one to fit their theology so I am going to continue using NASB, which I hear is regarded as the most accurate.<br>
<br>
For this discussion however lets use the word you chose "symbolizes."  You then go on to give your opinion of it rather than using the words it uses.  Here is what you are saying it may say if you substitiure the NIV word.  <br>
<br>
"And symbolizing that, baptism now saves you—not the removal of dirt from the flesh, but an appeal to God for a good conscience — through the resurrection of Jesus Christ."<br>
<br>
Am I correct?  I looked in the KJV, NIV, NAS, NASB, and the Greek and all say "baptism now saves you."<br>
<br>
Now, you don't have to like it, but you can't get past that fact.  Even if it said "corresponding to the fact that grass is green baptism now saves you" you could not argue that it isn't baptism that saves you, you could only argue in what way the fact that "grass is green" is compared to the statement that "baptism now saves you."  <br>
<br>
<font color=yellow>Noah was saved by his faith in God not by flood waters or the ark and Peter knows this. </font color><br>
<br>
So, would you then reason that Noah would have been saved even if he disobeyed God and didn't build an ark?  No.  You are right that the Ark didn't save Noah, but you are jumping to the wrong conclusion from there.  The Ark did not save Noah, but without the Ark there Could have been no salvation.  God needed an ark? No, but God pre-planned the Ark as the method of salvation.<br>
<br>
<font color=yellow>Infact, the interpretation I offer is consistent with Romans 5:1 and Ephesians where we read that justification and salvation is by faith alone. </font color><br>
<br>
Okay, I am looking at Romans 5:1 now.  I don’t know what version you are looking at but I don’t see “alone” anywhere.  I see in the NASB it says: “Therefore having been justified by faith, we have peace with God through our Lord Jesus Christ,” which says that we have been justified and have peace with God through faith.  Now, you may take that as saying that faith alone justifies us, but if you do then you need to explain vs 8 and 9 of the same chapter that say “But God demonstrates His own love toward us, in that while we were yet sinners, Christ died for us. Much more then, having now been <b>justified by His blood</b>, we shall be saved from the wrath of God through Him.<br>
<br>
Hmm.. now, we have to either assume that vs 8-9 negate vs 1, or we have to assume that we are justified by both.  Now if we say that vs 1 is negated then we have to find out what laws of the Bible were written last because only they apply.  If we say that both are needed then how can you say that only faith is required, AND how can you say then that baptism which is claimed to justify, doesn’t justify?  Further, the Bible states that His blood is symbolized by baptism so then if we are justified by His blood… well, never mind, I will let you draw the obvious conclusion.<br>
<br>
Colossians 2:11-12<br>
11 and in Him you were also circumcised with a circumcision made without hands, in the removal of the body of the flesh by the circumcision of Christ;<br>
12 having been buried with Him in baptism, in which you were also raised up with Him through faith in the working of God, who raised Him from the dead.<br>
<br>
<font color=yellow>In Colossians 2:11-12 Paul calls this the "circumcision of the heart". Don't you think a Hebrew understood that it wasn't circumcision that made one a child of God? Paul obviously understood that circumcision is a symbolic ritual consecrating a work that has already been accomplished. Paul the Apostle of Christ likens baptism to the act (symbol) of circumcision. Sorry Cendan, but I will trust that St. Paul and St. Peter understand the words of Christ much better than you thank you.</font color><br>
<br>
First I don’t see anywhere that is “says” circumcision of the heart.  In fact it is referring to the sinful ways of the life before baptism.  Now, you were quick to point out the “corresponding to” in 1 Peter, are you now going to ignore that vs 12 is continuing from vs 11.?  Note in particular the word “having.”   Having been buried with Him in baptism they have been circumcised from the flesh.  In which they were ALSO raised up with Him THROUGH faith in the working of God.  I don’t know how to make that more clear, and anything I say would be redundant so I will wait to see how you respond to that.  <br>
Paul is NOT comparing baptism with circumcision.  He used the word to indicate the cutting away of the old life, and YES, he did use that term because they were familiar with it.  Do I have to point out again that he is talking to the church of Colossae and he assumes the fact that they are baptized?<br>
<br>
So, the Apostle Paul and Peter (not St. Peter except in the sense that ALL christians are saints) do understand the words of Christ better than me.  It seems that all 3 of us understand them better than you.  Paul is not talking about “a symbolic ritual consecrating a work that has already been accomplished” but rather he is comparing the, to be blunt, separation of the foreskin from the penis with the removal of the sinful way of man from the body.  In the same way it is used in Philippians 3:3  “for we are the true circumcision, who worship in the Spirit of God and glory in Christ Jesus and put no confidence in the flesh,”<br>
<br>
Anyway you look at it, he states that it happened because they were “buried with Him in baptism.”<br>
<br>
Also, I would like to hear your opinion on what Acts 2:38 says…<br>
<br>
38 And Peter said to them, "Repent, and let each of you be baptized in the name of Jesus Christ for the forgiveness of your sins; and you shall receive the gift of the Holy Spirit.<br>
<br>
Here is how I read it.<br>
<br>
Repent – command<br>
Be baptized – command<br>
In the name of Jesus Christ – command/method<br>
For the forgiveness of your sins – command/purpose<br>
And you shall receive the gift of the Holy Spirit. – promise/reward<br>
<br>
<br>
Curran, I am not attempting to flame or taunt.  I will admit that I tend to be sarcastic.  Either way I do not see anything I wrote to you as more inflammatory then the things you have said.  Example?  <font color=yellow>Sorry Cendan, but I will trust that St. Paul and St. Peter understand the words of Christ much better than you thank you.  </font color><br>
