Actually, a thorough analysis of scripture can be accomplished by comparing various texts. I don't subscribe to the idea that there is an &quot;annointed version&quot; of the Bible as some do. Personally, I can deal with what ever text you want. I may refer to other texts only to help clarify a point I am making. <br>
<br>
<br>
Before I begin I want to be perfectly clear that I firmly believe what Paul said, &quot;... we have redemption through his blood, the forgiveness of sins...&quot; (Eph 1:7). So let me ask you Cendan. Is it the blood of Christ that saves us or is it baptism?<br>
<br>
<br>
I want to start by dealing with Acts 2:38. &quot;Repent&quot; (2nd person plural) and &quot;be baptized&quot; (3rd person singular) and &quot;you will recieve the gift of the Holy Spirit&quot; (2nd person plural). Repent is a universal command to all people (Acts 17:30). &quot;Be baptized&quot; is specific to believers only (Acts 8:12).<br>
<br>
Acts 2:38 is saying &quot;repent&quot;, and you will receive the gift of the Holy Spirit, and each one of you (those who have already recieved the gift) be baptized in the name of Jesus Christ for the remission of sins. You should note the greek word for remission (aphesis) simply means &quot;release&quot;. Compare with Ephesians 1:7 where it is stated that it is through the blood of Christ that we obtain the aphesis (forgiveness) of sins! Cendan, do you need to go and find the literal blood of Christ and bathe in it in order to be forgiven? Of course not. It is clear that we are dealing with symbolic language. A good exegete will always consider passages with all that has been stated in the Bible concerning the topic at hand. That is why I pointed you to look at what Paul said about baptism. &quot;Baptism&quot; has always been a rite of passage in the Church. Those who are baptised are taking the mark of Christ and publicly declaring what happened to their hearts earlier. You know Paul said &quot;I thank God I baptised none of you....&quot; If he thought baptism was essential to salvation as you do, do you think he would have been thankful not to have baptised? Acts 2:38 means to be baptized for (because of) the forgiveness of sins. We aren’t baptized &quot;to get&quot; forgiveness of sin. Rather, because our sins have been forgiven, we should be baptized.<br>
<br>
